В§0     В§0В§o бҙЎКҖЙӘбҙӣбҙӣбҙҮЙҙ КҷКҸ ЙўбҙӣбҙҖЙӘбҙ 
#- В§1В§lпј‘. пј°пҪ’пҪ…пҪҒпҪҚпҪӮпҪҢпҪ…В§0
В§0
В§0Although it is only natural that a text proudly portraying a controversial title will receive mixed reception, it does not necessarily mean that the text in question aims to disrupt, to anger
#- and to upset. Rather, many controversial works in the Civcraft community, including this one, have had a specific and rather non-threatening goal: to induce conversation, to facilitate the spread of ideas, and, more specifically, to lay out a hypothesis, 
#- a theory and a demonstration, all in one, packaged into a small book- for the pleasure of the uninformed reader.В§0
В§0
В§0Rather than to take this book as being yet another unoriginal bandwagonning critique of Civcraft 3.0, I encourage you to 
#- think of it rather as a cultural analysis of the unfolding social instability within the Civcraft community, and what happens when administrators fall too far out of touch with the majority of the playerbase.
#- В§1В§lпј’. пјЁпҪүпҪ“пҪ”пҪҸпҪ’пҪүпҪғпҪҒпҪҢ пјЈпҪҸпҪҺпҪ”пҪ…пҪҳпҪ”В§0
В§0
В§0The Civcraft community is gripped social instability. A once-great server, considered by hundreds of players as being the only viable Minecraft server, now stands
#- shuttered. The world is bleak, griefed and deserted- small towns lie empty, small dirt shacks with petty meme signs litter the map, smouldering wreckage testifies to the countless squabbles and conflicts that simply fizzed out into the unmistakable void
#- of inactivity. Yet, only a couple of months ago, the laucnh of the widely-anticipated Civcraft 3.0 was attested to be the most popular launch in Civcraft's history, with hundreds upon hundreds of players filtering into the ripe and empty worlds of
#- Civcraft.В§0
В§0Even until the end of the second iteration, Civcraft stood unmatched and undefeated as the sole server in the CivStyle community, quashing all opposition and taking a lion's share of the CivStyle playerbase. Today, however, the story is very
#- different. The CivStyle playerbase has been fractured between many different CivServers, including В§0В§oDevotedВ§0, В§0В§oSovereigntyВ§0
В§0В§oAscendingВ§0, and В§0В§oCivclassicsВ§0, while Civcraft continues to see an exodus of spurned players. What happened to this once-
#- great server? What caused the fall of Civcraft?В§0
В§0
В§0Many answers have, of course, been proposed: theories have sprung up abundantly placing the blame at the feet of the playerbase, of unnamed third-party actors, and of the
#- nature of Minecraft itself. However, to truly define the issue that led to the collapse of an enduring and popular server, we must first go back in time, back to the earliest known period of Civcraft, the pre-HCF period.В§0
В§0
В§0The pre-HCF period
#- of Civcraft (sometimes referred to as Old Civraft) began immediately after the beginning of 1.0 in early 2012 and lasted until the first HCF invasion in December of the same year. The pre-HCF era was marked by the spread of the first and earliest
#- cultures. During the course of 2012, three main cultural groups were formed and spread out over the map: the Civvie cultural group (Civvies), the Roman cultural group (Romans), and the Spanish cultural group (Spainiards). Of these three groups, the most
#- dominant was, by far, the Civvie group that came to populate the entire map.В§0
В§0
В§0More specifically, the Civvie culture that existed in the pre-HCF era is today considered one of the many culture that are branches of the Civvie "mothergroup", the all
#- encompassing denomination that includes all Civcraftian cultures. Although today we know of dozens of such different Civvie  subcultures, there was only one such culture that existed in pre-HCF Civcraft. Today, it is know as В§0В§oOld Civvie.В§0

#- It was during this brief period of cultural homogenity that the Civcraft admin team was convened and cemented together. The leader of the team, Ttk2, used his power and charisma to consolidate a tight-knit group, with its ideals closely intertwined with
#- the greater Old Civvie cultural agenda. Due to the demographic makeup of the budding server, it was only natural that the entirety of the admin team was composed of Old Civvies. In this pre-HCF era of twentysomething-year-old players, widespread anarcho-
#- capitalism, and pro-feminist viewpoints, the admin team and the wide majority of the playerbase found themselves in perfect cultural balance. Coincidentally, it is often this era that is lauded as being the "ideal" and "purest" form of Civcraft, untainted
#- by contrarian cultural groups upsetting the delicate balance of gameplay.В§0
В§0
В§0However, with the first HCF invasion and the beginning of the HCF war, the pre-HCF period of Civcraft came to an end, and the cultural dominance of Old Civvies was
#- shattered as a new cultural group was brought in by the HCF invaders, who began to settle in the server. The first new culture to arrive upon the server was В§0В§ovoucherismВ§0 (derived from the proto-factions term "to vouch [for]"). These vouchers, former
#- raiders and members of the hundred-strong HCF invader groups, slowly settled into Civcraft and began to adapt and assimilate into the server. However, the rapid and violent contact between the Old Civvies and the Vouchers resulted in many massacres,
#- often committed by the militarily-superior vouchers. Over the course of the year, the unrelenting voucher influence created a new branch of Civvie culture termed В§0В§oNew CivvieВ§0 (or Neo-Civvie), one that would come to almost completely replace the Old
#- Civvie branch after a couple of years. Furhermore, the cultural diversification of the server would not stop there: the second great migration of a new culture, the В§0В§oChannersВ§0, would occur in late 2014 and early 2015. However, all
#- throughout these extreme cultural shifts to the server, the admin team remained the same- a small, contained bubble of Old Civvie culture, cut off from their cultural kin, once the inhabitants of this vast server but reduced to small pockets in
#- danger of extinction and assimilation from other cultures.В§0
В§0
В§0The reason it is important to talk about culture in this case is because the cultural makeup of the server was more than an inconsequential byproduct of roll-play, much like
#- player-created "religions" were during a brief period in the 2.0 map. A player's culture defines how they think, how they interact with others and, ultimately, how they will treat Civcraft. A group's culture will therefore mean the difference between a 
#- well-meaning one or a nefarious one, a raiding group and a protectionist group, an individually-minded group or a collectivist group. Naturally, cultures have far-reaching implications beyond simple heritage, and, more importantly, most cultural groups
#- are widly different between themselves. This is why the fact that Civcraft's Ttk2ist administration team, a pocket of archaic Old Civviism, created the admin-player divide that eventually tore the entire server apart.
#- В§1В§lпј“. пјҙпҪҲпҪ… пј©пҪҺпҪ–пҪҒпҪ“пҪүпҪҸпҪҺ пјҰпҪ…пҪҒпҪ’В§0
В§0
В§0One of the most prominent and destructive side effects of the Old Civvie administration group running a server where their mentality died out years ago is one that is well-documented and pervasive among Old
#- Civvie-cultured players: the fear of a new HCF invasion.В§0
В§0
В§0The reasons for this particular fear being rampant within the Old Civvie community are obvious, as the Old Civvies were the first to come in contact with the wildly different Vouchers and
#- witnessed the utter devestation that the first HCF wars brought upon their community. Indeed, early Civcraft suffered a series of HCF invasions; however there was a direct correlation between the diminishing population of the Old Civvies and the
#- potency and destructiveness of the ensuing HCF invasions in the first part of the second map. This can be explained mostly by the heightened ability of New Civvies to fight vouchers on a military level, and the closer cultural link between the
#- voucher-influenced New Civvies and the vouchers themselves.В§0
В§0
В§0As the fear of repeating HCF invasions slowly disappeared in the general population of Civcraft, it persisted in the administration team and led to a series of unpopular decisions
#- that only furthered the divide between admins and players. These seemingly misplaced decisions, such as the famous banning of Phac3d or the "e-rape" bans can be understood when they are analyzed through the cultural angle. It then becomes apparent that 
#- the admin team took such anti-HCF actions due to the pervasive fear, impregnated into the Old Civvie mind, that the Voucher would be directly responsible for the death of Civcraft and thus needed to be stopped.В§0
В§0
В§0The most apparent results of this
#- uniquely Old Civvy fear, however, came with the makeover of Civcraft that was 3.0. One of the biggest elements of 3.0 that caused Civcraft to tear itself apart was what many players referred to as "the grind", the needless difficulty to progress along any
#- kind of technology tree, something that gives Civcraft its characteristic addictive qualities. When analyzing these decisions through the cultural lens, we can see that the Old Civvie admin team ended up ruining the addictive qualities of Civcraft through
#- their pervasive emotional scars resulting from the devestation of the first HCF invasion. The result was an unsatisfying game, where everyone is blocked from progressing along the tech tree due to the possibility of unnamed "HCF invaders" doing
#- the same, even though a modern-day HCF invasion is impossible, simply due to the cultural makeup of the current CivStyle community.
#- В§1В§lпј”. пјЈпҪҸпҪҺпҪғпҪҢпҪ•пҪ“пҪүпҪҸпҪҺВ§0
В§0
В§0Unfortunately, the ultimate reason for the death of Civcraft was the cultural distance that the admin team took with regards to their playerbase. This cultural difference affected their mindset, and caused them to take highly
#- unpopular decisions with regards to the direction of the server. These actions, ultimately, had the result of driving out a large majority of their playerbase, causing the rise of other CivServers, such as В§0В§oDevotedВ§0, ran by Bonkill's New Civvie
#- administration.В§0
В§0
В§0Currently, Civcraft seems to be in its death throes. The slow exodus of all but the most grind-minded players continues, and the daily activity has flatlined at 0 active players. Rather than reversing their decisions and
#- attempting to save the server, the admin team continues to maintain that the policies of 3.0 are accurate.В§0
В§0Furthermore, the last pocket of Old Civviism, the admin team itself, seems to be in danger of breaking up from internal issues, with Ttk2's
#- resignation looming on the horizon. It is perhaps possible that by the time power and control of the server is wrested from the hands of the Ttk2ist Old Civvie ultraminority, no amount of reversed changes will fix the irreparable damage to Civcraft.
#- 
#- 
